r:abstractText>&lt;p>Whilst research on the impact of leadership behaviour on organisational, unit, group and employee effectiveness is extensive, the impact on employee attitudes and behaviours is less well developed and rather neglected in comparison. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research will focus on the roles and experiences of&amp;nbsp; 'followers' to offer an alternative perspective on leadership to that found in the mainstream leadership literature. Leaders are involved in dynamic, two-way relationships with those they lead; followers are not passive recipients of leadership. The attitudes and characteristics of followers, and their interactions with one another, are important parts of their role as 'co-producers', both in terms of the effectiveness of leadership styles and outcomes. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>An in-depth, exploratory qualitative case study will focus on experience-centred narratives within a professional services firm as an example of how followers may experience and influence leadership styles and contribute to organisational outcomes. This approach will capture rich descriptions and understanding, witnessing novel leadership practices not detailed in the literature and providing a basis for analysing relationships between leadership approaches and employee attitudes. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>50752</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Ill-judged humour may create friction at work</gtr:description><gtr:form>A magazine, newsletter or online publication</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>E5865B37-7729-4E27-A214-322A1DA96BD0</gtr:id><gtr:impact>An article in FT Adviser based on the research

